{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_queenofspades_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280608695/1958012601/0665.xml":{"full_text":"ANKARA TALKS\nDifficult Mission\nFaces Dulles\nView From\nWashington\nBj MID THEROUX\nMar Stall WrtWr\nThe recent Soviet stuck on the\nBaghdad poet and participation\nin its Annual conference by Sec\nretary of State Dulles is certain\nto brine new pressures on the\nUnited States to assume full for\nmal membership in the pact.\nThat is the belief of many West\nern diplomats here on the eve of\nthe opening of the Ankara talks.\nThe Baghdad pact, which unites\nTurkey, Iraq. Britain. Pakistan\nand Iran in a \u201cnorthern tier\" de\nfensive alliance against any Com\nmunist aggression in the area,\nwas the 1956 result of a 1953 sug\ngestion by Mr. Dulles. The United\nStates has never joined as a full\nfledged member, although Ameri\ncan representatives sit on the\neconomic. miliUry, and antisub\nversive committees of the alliance\nand American observers have at\ntended all the major pact meet\nings.\nThe Dulles policy has been to\nwithhold formal alignment with\nthe pact\u2014officially the Middle\nEast Treaty Organisation\u2014in or\nder to make United States rela\ntions with the Arab states more\nflexible.\nHostility to the pact among the\nArab nations, led by Egypt and\nSyria, has intensified since Its in\nception. reaching an especially\nbitter pitch after the British-\nFrench-Israeli attack on Egypt in\n1939. Mr. Dulles has sought to\n\u201chold the door open\" to improved\nrelations with the Arab nations in\nthe hope that a more favorable\nclimate might lead to Arab par\nticipation in a widened Middle\nEast anti-Communist alliance.\nPressure Grows\nWith Moscow attitude stiffen\ning and Arab support lacking,\nBritish desire for American mem\nbership in the pact has increased.\nThe British, as well as the states\nmen of the other pact members,\nparticularly Turkey and Pakistan,\nare urging official American ad\nherence to the alliance as a prac\ntical necessity. American policy\nin the Middle East, they have\nwarned, requires all-out support\nand participation by the leader\nof the Western alliance. In this\nview, nothing further is to be\ngained by shunning membership\nin the pact.\nMr. Dulfes has announced that\nthe United States intends no\nChange in its relations with the\nalliance at thig time. His visit\nto the Ankara conference, he has\nindicated, is intended only to\nreinvigorate the pact lending\npersonal prestige to its deliber\nations, The Secretary os several\noccasions has pointed out that the\nso-called Elsenhower doctrine for\nthe Middle East, approved by\nCongress last spring, wss in\ntended as a substitute for formal\nAmerican membership.\nUnder the terms of the Etoen\n-1 tower doctrine, the United Slates\npledget support. Including armed\nintervention, to any Middle East\nern nation threatened with Com\nmunist aggression.\nCritics of the Dulles approach\ncontend that developments in the\nMiddle East have already shown\nclearly that Arab nationalism, in\nall the Arab states, will never\npermit general Arab adherence to\nthe Baghdad alliance. Even pro-\nWestern Lebanon, they point out.\nrefrains from association with it.\nThus the alternatives, they insist,\nare U> for the United States to\ngo all-out in support and member\nship In the pact, consolidating\nwhat strength It now has and\nabandoning fruitless efforts to win\nArab support, or <2> to drop the\npact entirely, in favor of some\nnew arrangement to insure Arab\nindependence of Communist in\nfluences.\n>hun Involvement\nProponents of the latter al\nemative hold that the Arab na\ntions, Including Egypt and Syria,\nhave no intention to become So\nviet satellites. Egyptian President\nNasser in particular is considered\ndetermined to keep his nation\naloof from outright Soviet ties,\nwhile at the same time accepting\nRed military and economic as\nsistance. Syrian spokesmen have\nvoiced the same Intentions and\ninsist their noninvolvement policy\nis feasible.\nBut the newly organized Asian-\nAfrlcan Solidarity Conference,\nwhich met in Cairo this month,\ndemonstrated so unmistakable a\nCommunist domination that Col.\nNasser himself was reported dis\nmayed* To the West, the confer\nence Afclosed a pro-Soviet dls\npositldgi among the Arab and other\nnations (Bat spelled grave danger\nto the Baghdad pact, even the\npossible withdrawal of Iraq and\npossibly Iran as a result of grow\ning pressure from anti-Western\nnationalism. Mr. Dulles' visit to\nAnkara is one result of such dis\nquieting possibilities.\nFor the present at least, Mr.\nDulles seems decided to make no\nmajor change in American policy\ntoward the Middle East. He has\npointed to the Elsenhower doc\ntrine\u2019s offer of support to any\n\u201cgroup of nations\" in the Middle\nEast resisting Communist agdrea\nsion as a pledge of full military\naid to the Baghdad pact as well\nas to individual states. Meanwhile,\nthe economic aid authorized in the\nElsenhower doctrine az approved\nby congressional resolution, he be\nlieves. will strengthen the recipient\nnations and work to Improve Arab\nattitudes toward American policy.\nNearly 1199 million has already\nbeen committed. $12.3 million ear\nmarked for military purposes.\nBut reports from Ankara on the\neve of the conference promise\nheavy pressure on Mr. Dulles for\nfull American participation in the\npact, with greatly increased\nAmerican financial and military\nML\nView From\nThe U. N.\nBy NED MAKDIBI\nSpecial WriMr .orTbtaur\nUNITED NATIONS. N. Y \u2014The\nattention of every Middle Eastern\ndelegate to the United Nations is\nriveted this week end on Ankara,\nwhen the Baghdad pact nations\nwill begin their two-week confer\nence Monday. And one has only to\ndiscuss the meeting witl those\ndelegatee to realise the difficulties\nSecretary of State Dulles faces In\nhis efforts to keep the West's Arab\nbloc Intact.\nIt Is clear, of course, that Mos\ncow's long-range goal t> to replace\nWestern powers in the Middle\nEast. But in the opinion of most\nArab observers, the immediate So\nviet objective to to neutralize the\narea militarily: that is, to preclude\nits us* by both East and West.\nThat approach has some appeal to\nnationalist Arab elements.\nThis objective was made clear\nlast week, it is felt, when a spokes\nman for the Soviet Foreign Min\nistry warned Middle Eastern\ncountries that the United States\nwas planning, through the pact,\nto set up nuclear missile bases\nwithin their boundaries, which\nwould be a threat to their exist\nence and to their religious shrines.\nSensitive Target\nThe atheistic and antireliglous\nphilosophy of communism, which\nto well-known to the Arabs, adds\nhypocrisy to the absurdity of that\nwarning, as the American State\nDepartment has pointed out. The\nfact remains that the Soviet Union\nwas cleverly aiming at a most\nsensitive spot\u2014Arab religious feel\nings\u2014in its effort to arouse a\npreconference wave of resentment\nagainst the pact and against the\nUnited States as its sponsor.\nIt to accepted here, however,\nthat the Arab masses do not need\nany extra Impetus to their an\ntagonism toward the pact. Ounng\nthe last two weeks the Arab press,\neven in pro-Western Lebanon, has\nbeen vehemently attacking the\nAnkara conference. An influen\ntial Cairo newspaper declared in\nan editorial last week that the\nrecent \u201cunofficial\" Asian-African\nconference In Cairo\u2014with its\nstrong pro-Communtot tone\u2014has\nall but wrecked the Baghdad pact\nand brought Mr. Dulles to Ankara\nto try and mend the damage.\nThe leading magazine in Leba\nnon implied that Mr. Dullas has\nbecome convinced of the futility\nof the pact as a defensive ar\nrangement in the Middle East.\nEven in Iraq, the Baghdad pact to\nreprtted to be unpopular among\nthe masses who feel, rightly or\nwpanglr. It has caused dis\nunity among the Arab states.\nReasons Ascribed\nIf such be the feeling In the\nMiddle East toward the Baghdad\npact, what then to the purpose of\nMr. Dulles' decision to attend the\nAnkara meeting? Middle East\nobservers here ascribe three rea\nsons for the Secretary's trip:\nFirst, they say. in spite of the\nfact that the West has lost con\nsiderable ground in the Middle\nEast, the srea has not been al\ntogether written off as a Western\nsphere of influence. Mr. Dulles'\npresence in Ankara will lend pres\ntige to the conference and give the\npro-Western Mideast nations a\nmuch-needed shot of confidence.\nSecond. Mr. Dulles' trip to seen\nhere as some evidence that the\nUnited States seeks to shift the\nemphasis from military to eco\nnomic programs in the Middle\nEast. The Secretary will argue,\nit is predicted, that an increase In\nthe economic aspects of the Bagh\ndad pact will help to popularize\nit. at the same time offsetting the\nlatest Bovlet economic offensive in\nthe area. While Soviet propaganda\ncould be. and in fact has been,\nvery effective against the military\nnature of the pact, it can achieve\nvery little in denouncing an al\nliance of mutual economic co\noperation among Middle Eastern\ncountries.\nThird. Mr. Dulles is expected to\n''insult with our allies in the Mid\nlie East on matters pertaining to\ntheir area which might be dis\ncussed in a summit meeting be\ntween the United States and the\nSoviet Union\u2014should there be one.\nBy conferring with them and\nsounding their opinion, he will\ngive the impression that the\nUnited States will not take uni\nlateral decisions affecting the\nMiddle East in the event of a\nmeeting.\nPoints for Speculation\nThere has been much specula\ntion on two major questions per\ntaining to the Ankara conference:\nM> Will the United States Join\nthe Baghdad pact, and <2> will\nany other Middle Eastern nations\nbe likely to join?\nThe pact members have been\nInsisting that the United States\nbecome a full-fledged member of\ntheir organization. The three Mid\ndle East members argue that since\nthe United States to now in the\nprocess of Ailing the vacuum cre\nated as a consequence of Britain's\nparticipation in the 1936 invasion\nof Egypt, it is imperative that\nIt participate fully in the activi\nties of the alliance.\nIraq, in particular, is most\nanxious to see the United States\ncome in. because of the great loss\nof prestige Britain has suffered\namong Arabs following the Suez\ninvasion.\nArab sources here, however, do\nnot expect the United States to\nloin the pact at this fneeting. Nor\ndo they expect the pact to gain\nnew Arab support at this time.\nIt to felt that Jordan, Lebanon,\nand Saudi Arabia, while in general\nfriendly to the West, are conscious\nof adverse public opinion among\nthe Arab maaaes to the pact.\nj Therefore they will not join, y\nEditorials\nEditorial Articles\nTHE WEEK IN PERSPECTIVE\nAdvice from the Senate\nWhen the military significance\nof the bovlet Union's first sputnik\nbecame apparent after the launch\ning last October 4. a political\nscramble among lawmakers, ad\nministration officials, and military\nleaders began over blame for the\nominous disparity between the\npage of American and Russian\n\u25a0cMAUfle and military advanced\nIn the first wave of reactiogf\nthere was a not unnatural ten\ndency to exaggerate past deficien\ncies and to level charges based on\nhindsight. Initial efforts Inside\nthe Eisenhower administration to\nshrug off the Soviet satellite as a\n\u201cgadget\" fell before the near\npanic, But even that early, there\nwere counsels of calmness and\npatience. One of them came from\nthe Senate Majority Leader. Sen\nator Lyndon Johnson. Democrat\npf Texas.\nSenator Johnson started an\nimmediate investigation of the\nUnited States defense situation,\nparticularly in the apparent lag\nin the field of guided missiles and\nrocket power. But in calling his\nSenate Subcommittee on Pre\nparedness together. In advance of\nthe regular convening at Congress,\nthe Benate leader pledged as non\npolitical an inquiry as he could get\nfrom an election-year Congress.\nLast Thursday, the Johnson\nsubcommittee concluded the 110-\nday initial phase of its Investiga\ntion and submitted a unanimous\n\"statement in the nature of an\ninterim report\u201d to the Senate.\nThe statement, written by Chair\nman Johnson and subscribed to\nby the four Democrats and three\nRepublicans on the subcommittee,\nadhered to the chairman's pledge.\nIt leveled no charges and assessed\nno blame, but set forth in general\nterms a 17-point program for\n\u201cdecisive action\" in the \u201crace for\nsurvival\" with the Soviet Union.\nThe statement summarized the\nconclusions drawn by the probers\nafter weeks of testimony from 70\nwitnesses and advice from some\n200 experts.\nThe summary of the facts, the\nstatement said, \u201cdo not give cause\nfor comfort. But we do not con\nsider them a cause for despair\nand hopelessness. We regard them\nas a challenge to all Americans.\"\nThe Recommendation\nTO meet the challenge, the Sen\nators recommended particularly\nreorganisation of the Defense De\npartment (without spelling out\nthe type of reorganization): rapid\nacceleration in the development\nprogram for operational guided\nmissiles: prompt search for a\nrocket motor capable of delivering\na thrust of 1 million pounds (in\neffect, a thrust sufficient to guar\nantee access to outer space*: an\nintense effort toward development\nof an antimissile missile, an effec\ntive antisubmarine missile defense\nand a missile attack warning net\nwork: and greatly Increased\nconcern with basic research.\nCarefully avoiding the placing\nof blame for the Soviet gain over\nAmerican weaponry and science,\nthe subcommittee said simply:\n\"The past to already for historians.\nLet us seek solutions so that the\nfuture may be written by free\nworld historians.\"\nBut no effort was made to mini\nmize the significance of Soviet\naccomplishments: on the contrary,\nthe subcommittee's statement\nconceded bluntly that the Russians\nhave outdistanced the West in d)\ndevelopment of ballistic missiles:\n(2) submarine building: Oft speed\nof development of new weapons:\n(4) first conquest of outer spaces\n<s> the education and training of\nscientists and technicians.\nBut the subcommittee declared,\nhowever, that \u201cthere to nothing In\nthe record to Indicate that Amer\nica has lost Us vitality or its ca\npacity to produce In time whatever\nwe need to retain our present\npower to strike devastating blows\n\u2014blows of almoto total destruc\ntion\u2014at any aggressor.\"\nEven while the Senate group's\nreport was being made, the House\npassed. 386 to 0. the emergency\n$1.26 billion supplemental funds\nbill for the Defense Department,\nwhich had been requested in the\nwake of the sputnik's dismaying\nappearance on the radar-tracking\nscreens. The extra-money measure\nwent promptly to the Senate,\nwhere equally swift approval to\ncertain. The funds will be added\nto the military appropriation for\nthe current fiscal year, and will be\nused to finance additional efforts\non missile programs and on estab\nlishing an \u201couter apace\" agency\nin the Pentagon.\nPolitics Steps In\nThe Johnson subcommittee's\nstudied avoidance of political\novertones was not shared by\nothers, however. Last week Pres\nidential Assistant Sherman Adams\nIn a Republican Party speech at\nChicago, belabored the Democrats\nIn harsh terms as the party to\nblame for a long list of woes, par\nticularly in foreign and military\npolicy. (See section below titled\n\u201cPolitical Front.\")\nFor the Democrats, the articu\nlate Senator Fulbrlght of Arkansas,\nsenior member of the Senate For\neign Relations Committee, lashed\nat the Eisenhower administration\nin a bitter Senate speech. He\ncharged the administration had.\nafter five years of \u201cinadequacy 1\nand lack of positive leadership,\nleft the Nation \"fat and immobile.\u201d\nForeign policy, the Arkansan de\nclared, was based on the John\nFoster Dulles \"doctrinal line\" that\nSoviet communism was a failure\nand must collapse, a line the Sen\nator found fallacious in the face\nof Soviet accomplishments.\nBut it was on education that\nthe Arkansas Senator, a former\nRhodes scholar and university\npresident, assailed the Elsenhower\nadministration moat severely.\nA \"general climate of\nfI)C Sunday fsfctf\nWASHINGTON, D. C. f JANUARY 26, 1958\nft\u2019. I A\u2014H ft\nV. m-\nVs j\nSKr I mb\nW I\nW 11 1\niVi \u2018Jlk. J\n\n1.1 W\\ ff\nr f 'ipS|\nJBfl\nTflilr \u2014jHHpNfct t.\nSENATOR Lyndon Johnson and Gen. James Gavin, retiring Army research chief, confer at hearings which produced 17-point defense report\ntellectuallsm.\" he charged, had\npaved the way for American\nweakness in public learning and\na society in which unskilled\nworkers were often paid more than\ncollege professors and \"an Elvis\nPresley makes more than the\nPresident of the United States\nIn education and learning, he de\nclared. would the final conflict\nbetween the Soviet and American\nsystems be resolved.\nWith Senator Johnson still\ncarrying the defense ball. Senator\nFulbright's address was taken as\nconfirms non that the Democrats\nin Congress meant to try hard to\nhold the initiative in the post\nsputnik era. Republican defense\nof the administration in the field\nof foreign and military policy has\nso far been characterised by the\ncontention that administration\nefforts have been neutralised by\nthe Democratic -controlled Con\ngress.\nDulles' Mission:\nFence Mending\nWhile Congress wanned up to\nits controversies and the adminis\ntration studied moves to speed the\nmissiles programs and strengthen\nthe Nation's general defenses.\nSecretary of State Dulles was off\nto the Middle East on another\nfence-mending mission. He will\nrepresent the United States as\nhead of an \"observer'* delegation\nat the annual council of the\nBaghdad pact in Ankara begin\nning tomorrow. En route Mr.\nDulles stopped at Marrakech,\nMorocco, and at Tehran. Iran's\ncapital, for talks with government\nofficials.\nMr. Dulles has indicated that\nhis trip to Ankara is Intended only\nas a morale-builder for the anti\ncommunist Baghdad pact nations\nsee stories by Fred Theroux and\nNed Makdlsi on this page). But\nreports from the Turkish capital\nsuggest that the Baghdad alliance\n\u2014Turkey. Iran. Iraq. Pakistan\nand Britain\u2014will press the Sec\nretary for more than morale.\nFormal United States membership\nin the Dulles-sponsored alliance\nis most desired; failing that much,\nthen a greatly increased program\nof American economic and mili\ntary aid will be sought.\nThe American Secretary of\nState s visit to the Baghdad pact\nsession brought familiar Soviet\nwarnings that he would seek to\n\"force\" the pact members to per\nmit United States missile bases\non their soils. But the State De\npartment categorically dented any\nsuch intentions, and dispatches\nfrom Britain and other member\nnations seem to confirm the denial.\nSoviet concern with the Dulles\nvisit to Ankara was disclosed Mon\nday, when the Soviet Foreign\nMinistry summoned reporters to\na special, hill-dress press confer\nence.\nA lengthy statement of the So\nviet charges was read to the news\nmen. Besides the missiles allega\ntion, the Russian statement also\nblasted the timing of the Ankara\nmeeting as provocative at a time\nwhen the world was still studying\nthe proposals of Soviet Premier\nNikolai Bulganin for a \"summit\"\nmeeting to attempt settlement of\nthe East-West areas of tension.\nSupport of Policy\nWestern replies to Mr. Bulganin,\nhowever, were uniformly negative.\nMost recent was that of West\nOerman Chancellor Adenauer on\nTuesday. Mr. Adenauer echoed the\nDulles rejection or high-level talks\nat this time, urging instead nego\ntiations on the diplomat level as\na necessary preliminary if later\nsummit talks were to have a chance\nof success. The West Oerman\nleader also suggested to the Soviet\nleaders that the public exchange*\nof letters between heads of state\nleft much to be desired If results\nwere sincerely sought.\nFormer Secretary o| State Dean\nAcheson, although attacking the\nEisenhower administration's for\neign policy and military leadership\nas one substituting \u201cwords for\nacts.\u201d nevertheless supported the\nDulles rejection of an early sum\nmit meeting with the Russians.\nPair of Visits\nSoviet Ambassador Georgi Za\nroubln. departing for Moscow and\na Foreign Office poet next week,\npaid a visit to Vice Presidebt\nNixon Friday at the Capitol. Un\nusually affable, he told newsmen\nafter the meeting that he and Mr.\nNixon had exchanged views on\nbroadening cultural relations be\ntween the peoples of the Bovlet\nUnion and the United States. An\nagreement on that subject to near\ncompletion after many weeks of\nnegotiation at the state De\npartment.\nThe Russian diplomat described\nthe 42-minute conversation as\ncordial and Informal. He said \u201cI\nassured Mr. Nixon that the Soviet\nUnion has no other purpose but\nto work in the direction of\nstrengthening peace and estab\nlishing friendly relations with the\nAmerican people.\u201d He explained\nhe had considered President Eisen\nhower s \"heavy schedule\u201d in de\nciding to visit the Vice President\ninstead.\nIn Moscow there was another\nambassadorial visit. The American\nenvoy. Uewelyn Thompson, who\nto returning to Washington for\nconsultations this week, called at\nthe Soviet Foreign Ministry. He\nasked Foreign Minister Andrei\nOromyko for an early renlv t\"\nMr. Elsenhower's proposals of\nJanuary 12. contained in his a\nswer to the Bulganin letter. Mr.\nOromyko told Mr. Thompson that\nthe reply was under study, and\nTHE NATIONAL SCENE\nThe Economy: Hopeful Look Ahead\n*Ai look ahead in 1956, thtra art\nftatndt far asMchnj that the decline\nin bninrM activity need net be pro\nlonged end that economic growth con\nbo returned without oettndod inter\nrapt ion. Tbo policies of Government\nwill be directed toward helping te\nat tore (bra remit\nThis statement of optimism In\nPresident Eisenhower's Economic\nReport, sent to Congress last week,\nmore or less echoed the hopes he\nheld out In his budget message a\nweek earlier. There he estimated\nthat Federal revenues would reach\n6744 billion in the 1939 fiscal\nyear, permitting a precariously\nbalanced budget.\nAlthough the Economic Repoit\ndid not specifically detail the rea\nsons for this optimism, there are\nobvious signs that a hopeful out\nlook to Justified. The President's\neconomic advisers, in preparing\nthe report for him. no doubt were\nlooking to these factors:\nThe normal population g.cwth\nof 3 million persons a year cre\nating new markets and expanding\nold ones.\nEarly plans for letting hefty\ncontracts for missile research and\nproduction, plus a contemplated\n$2 billion to be spent by Uncle\nSam for highway construction.\nThe Inevitable replacing of In\nventories by businesses (hat last\nyear held back on new purchases\nwhile depleting unusually large\nstocks.\nA slight recovery in new I ous\ning starts that began some time\nago and shows signs of a con\ntinuing rise. (Residential construc\ntion is one of those economic\nweathervanes that permit long\nrange projection.)\nBut a minority report, more\npessimistic, might also find con\nsiderable agreement among some\neconomists. It would be founded\non a numbei* of the sensitive,\nlong-term economic indicators\nthat herald rises and declines\nlong before they show up In the\npaycheck or the pocketbook. For\nexample:\n\"the Soviet government would give\nits comments in due course.\"\nVanguard Ready?\nWith diplomatic maneuvers and\nregional alignments going their\nusual course, with a touch of\nadded urgency but a definitely\nmultiplied meaning, the missile\ntest base at Cape Canaveral. Fla.,\ngave long distance Indications\nlast week that a new American\neffort to fire a satellite Into space\nwas imminent.\nA Vanguard rocket, similar to\nthat of December 6 which failed,\nwas visible to distant beach ob\nservers. set nose-up oh its launch\ning pad. But it was not fired,\nalthough preparations appeared\nto be In progress.\nAnd on Friday the Atomic\nBnergy Commission announced\nthat its scientists had made\n\u201cfruitful and promising'' expert\nmenu in the effort to harness the\npower of fusion\u2014the H-bomb re\naction\u2014to peaceful purposes.\nAEC Chairman Lewis L. Strauss\nwarned that actual attainment of\nthe objective was \u201cyears sway.\"\nAt the same time, he denied that\nthe United SUtes. at his behest,\nhad held up a British announce\nment of progress in the same field\nwhich was ready some months\nago.\nVenezuela:\nUpheaval\nFive years of military dictator\nship came to a violent end in oil\nrich Venezuela last week. Restless\nness under the iron grip of Oen.\nMarcos Perez Jimenez and his\n\u00fcbiquitous security police had\ncome to a head on New Year s Day.\nThe average number of hours\nworked per week in manufactur\ning cqntinues downward.\nA steady decline in new incor\nporations. indicating uncertainty\nin the business community.\nThe spot market price index,\noff about 6 points since August,\npoints to a continued sluggish\nness over a wide area.\nThe slow rate of new orders\nshows that inventory liquidation\nIs still widespread.\nBeyond these points is the\nquestion of union wage demapds.\nComing contract negotiations,\nespecially in the automobile .in\ndustry, provide some cause for\napprehension. (See story by Wil\nliam Hines on Page A-23.) A new\nround of wage Increases would\ncertainly be used by business as\nan excuse to continue high pric\ning policies which could, alone,\nshatter Mr. Eisenhower\u2019s hopes\nfor a recovery around the middle\nof the year.\nPresidential Prescription\nIn his economic message, the\nPresident warned both business\nand labor that \"unwarranted\"\nprice and wage Increases could\neasily abort the recovery of eco\nnomic growth. But the \"policies\nof Government\" which he prom\nised would be used as a tonic to\nbe-taken-as-needed are of proved\npotency.\nOne of them was put into action\nthe day after the President sent\nhis report to Congress. The Fed\neral Reserve Board approved a\nreduction In the discount rate\u2014\nthe fee on loans to member banks\n\u2014of the Federal Reserve Bank of\nPhiladelphia, an action that is us\nually extended to other districts.\nThe cut In the rate from 3 per\ncent to 2*4 per cent was the sec\nond In two months and was gen\nerally Interpreted az a move by\nthe Board to enliven the lagging\neconomy. The new rate will prove\nattractive to Investors, thus in\nducing expansion, which,\nGeneral News\nEducation\nwith a short-lived Air Force re\nvolt. speedily suppressed by tha\ndictator\u2019s troops. But the ferment\ncontinued. This time with a shad\nowy civilian leadership, rioting\nbroke out in Caracas and a gen\neral strike was called for Tuesday.\nThe strike spread quickly. At\nfirst military units fought tha\nstreet crowds, but it soon was ap\nparent that the armed forcea\nwere not enthusiastic for their job.\nWhen several high-ranking officers\nof the army, navy and air fores,\nforsook Gen Perez Jimenez, the dig\nwas cast. After an ultimatum from\na hastily-formed military junta,\nthe dictator capitulated and fied\nat 3 am. Thursday for the Do\nminican Republic, where he was\nwelcomed by fellow dictator Tru\njillo.\nWith the flight of Perez Jimenes.\nthe civilian leadership revealed\nitself. Led by a young reporter\nfor the newspaper El Nacional.\nFabricio Ojeda, the \"Patriotic\nJunta\" was disclosed to be an\nefficient underground, surprisingly\nsuccessful in confusing the secret\npolice.\nThe new ruling junta, led by\nRear Admiral Wolfgang Larraza\nbal. quickly moved to restore sup\npressed freedoms and to abolish\ncensorship. It pledged loyalty to\ndemocracy and to the Catholie\nchurch, which on two previous\noccasions\u2014m Argentina and in\nColombia \u2014has been instrumental\nin toppling dictators when they\nharassed the clergy. But Caracas\nwas far from quiet yesterday,\ndespite popular enthusiasm for\nthe end of the dictatorship. Th#\ndemonstrated power of the civil\nian \"Patriotic Junta\" may bring\nnew clashes with the armed\nforces, traditionally the wieldera\nof state power in Venezuela.\nin turn, provides more jobs. It\nwill also have a strengthening ef\nfect on State and local funding\noperations, making needed new\nconstruction by States, countiea\nand cities less expensive to finance\nand therefore more inducing.\nThere was. m all likelihood, still\nanother reason for the Board*\naction. Although it would deny\nany motive involving support of\nthe Federal bond market, it no\ndoubt had in mind making tho\nupcoming refunding operations of\nthe Treasury less costly\nBeyond this, there* is the M\nbillion rise in the legal limit of\nthe national debt, a widened\nmargin which is expected to get\nfinal congressibnal approval this\nweek, and which will permit tho\nGovernment to increase its bor\nrowings in' the lean weeks ahead.\nCost of Living\nWhile the Government econ\nomists were watching the falling\neconomic indexes with apprehen\nsion. one index\u2014that which meas\nures the cost of living\u2014continued\nat its record level.\nIn what seemed at first glanoo\nan economic paradox, the con\nsumer price index in December\nremained unchanged at 121.6 per\ncent of the 1947-49 average. Ik\nwas only the second time in the\nlast 16 months that the index had\nnot climbed to new peaks. And\nhad it not been for the discounts\nauto dealers were offering to spur\nslow-moving car sales, the index\nwould have continued its climb,\nfor food prices moved higher\nThis is one of those indexes\nwhich economists refer to as a\nlagging indicator\"\u2014that is. in\nstead of pointing to a future\ntrend, it merely reacts to the past,\nlagging by as much as six months.\nAs for present conditions, they\nwere amply reflected in an an\nnouncement that one-third of thb\nNation's biggest industrial cen\nters had been designated as area*\non d-t#\nA-21","height":"29021","width":"18573"}}
